********************************<br>
<br>
Chapter 1: Childhood Dreams and Daring Deeds<br>
<br>
Half Elves have never been the most trusted folks in the land of Wyrdrake.  Since they are the children of both Elves and Men, they belong neither to one race nor the other, though, technically, they are a hybrid of both. I’m a Half Elf myself, the conflicted daughter of a Human father and an Elven mother, a wandering singer who traveled the world. Both of my parents were very well-respected in their own communities, yet the news of their betrothal displeased both their families. I can imagine my kinfolk saying: <br>
<br>
“You’re marrying a what? An Elf? Rhadmir, you’re out of your mind! Who is she?” <br>
<br>
“Annushka—you know that we Elves have to keep our lines pure! It’s our heritage!” <br>
<br>
“Now, I do understand you want to get married, old friend—but, Rhadmir, an Elf?!” <br>
<br>
“I’ve always loved you, Annushka, but this decision of yours may lead us to ruin!”   <br>
<br>
Racial prejudice has always been stronger on my mother’s side than my father’s, I think. Humans are pretty much tolerant of anyone, as long as they don’t cause trouble. Elves, on the other hand, can be picky when they’re approving partners for their children. They have to be Elves, first off, and secondly, they have to have such pure hearts that they’d never even think of treating their spouse badly. Once upon a time, Elves used to be totally pure, incorruptible and chivalrous to a fault, but now, through the influence of Men and all the other races in Wyrdrake, they’ve started to know the great lure of evil.<br>
<br>
I feel bad for the Elves—how some of them have abandoned their hearts to greed, hate and corruption—but then I can’t help thinking that’s not the way all the Elves are. Most of them are still good, although now they have to fight the same battles that Humans do—the eternal battles between good and evil, virtue and vice, in their hearts and souls.<br>
<br>
I don’t know how pure my heart is. I’ve tried to find out, but so far the local priests have always acted like they’re hiding something from me. Maybe I’m just naïve, or maybe they think I’m an ignorant little girl who can’t tell the difference between true faith and wishful thinking. I don’t know what to make of this. Somehow I hope that the Maker of this universe will have mercy on me, if he or she does exist. I myself think so.<br>
<br>
Is this faith? I don’t know. Such questions are best left up to the priests, I guess. <br>
<br>
Oh, my goodness! I’ve completely forgotten to introduce myself, what with all my rattling on! My name is Ytra, daughter of Annushka, the Elven bard, and Rhadmir, the dashing, valiant Human warrior who stole her heart. I know my name looks weird, but it’s pronounced “EE-truh,” or sometimes “IH-truh.” In Half-Elven slang, a hard-edged and rough combination of the Human and Elven tongues, my name means “perfect companion.” This makes me laugh. I certainly wasn’t a perfect companion when I was born! My mother and grandmother have told me many tales of how I howled and screamed. Mama said I was like one of the wild beasts, a little lioness cub, while Grandmama said that I simply had to grow into my lungs! I was very small for a baby.<br>
<br>
In fact, I was too small. My siblings and I were to be born in the wintertime, around all the Yuletide festivities that our village had. Our poor, dear, excited parents, Annushka and Rhadmir, were expecting the best holiday gifts they would ever get! Unfortunately, we came three months before Yuletide did, when summer was giving its last warm and hearty kiss to the lands of Wyrdrake. I was tiny and frail, weighing only three pounds at birth. No one thought I would live long. The Maker must have smiled upon me, though, for now I’m a lass of thirteen, waiting for life to begin, yet very impatient for it to start!<br>
<br>
I spent my childhood playing in the fields outside of our stone-walled town. Countless adventurers wandered in and out of our gates, looking for food and sleep at the inns or a drink at the local tavern. I wanted so much to be like these adventurers, clothed in various armors of metal and leather and chain, who strode confidently and boldly into circumstances unknown. I wished that someday I would be like them, and be one of them, but back then I was content to be simply a young girl, playing tag with my brothers and sisters on the grassy hills of the land that our sovereign owned. I was a happy child.<br>
<br>
I suspect one of the reasons I was so happy was because I knew my future was secure. Once a child reached the age of thirteen in our town, all the priests and the knights who served them would reveal the child’s destiny. No one was allowed to choose their own occupation or path, for the priests knew best, and, after all, the world was controlled by the Maker and his devout servants. I had little doubt that the priests would choose me to be an Adventurer, one of the highest classes or occupations that a child could ever get. <br>
<br>
My heart yearned for exploration and new knowledge. Did the priests know that?<br>
<br>
Our town was built upon six strong foundational classes: Warriors to protect us, Peasants to farm and work the land, skilled Artisans to build our homes and tools, Priests to heal us and guide us in spiritual matters, Adventurers to explore and conquer the wild, and, last and certainly least, Servants to help the other classes with their menial tasks. <br>
<br>
I thought the life of an Artisan wouldn’t be bad if I couldn’t be an Adventurer. Anything but a Servant. Servanthood was a position without honor, without glory, without respect. Only the priests gave the servants any special recognition, for they said that the lowest of all would someday become kings. I didn’t believe it. Many Servants in our town, I thought, with their kind and humble attitudes, would be wonderful kings, but in reality our leaders always came from the Warrior class. No Servant stood a chance when it came to gaining the throne. A Priest once tried to become king, but then a proud Warrior, challenging him to a duel, won the fight. The Priest left our town to wander the world, seeking spiritual guidance through self-denial and meditation. I admired him. <br>
<br>
My brothers and sisters were as varied as the colors of the rainbow. Jonathan, my oldest brother, resented his Elven heritage and wished he were only a Man. Strength was not one of the key attributes of the Elves, and Jonny was afraid that the priests were going to make him a Peasant instead of a Warrior. Nothing detested him more than the smell of manure in newly-plowed fields, or the wielding of a hoe and rake. He wanted to be a Warrior, young Jonny did, and I certainly hoped he would achieve his dream since birth.<br>
<br>
“If I were a Man,” he said, “instead of Half Elf, the Warriors wouldn’t call me weak!”<br>
<br>
I told Jonathan that he was never weak, no matter how strong he was, but Jon rarely listened. What would the opinions of his sister matter when he stood before the Priests?<br>
<br>
My sister Yelina, however, was very proud she had Elf blood. Not one for strenuous physical activity or the agricultural life of a peasant girl, Yelina strove for the Priesthood. Not that she’d be a bad Priest—her wisdom and loving advice were often sought by our family—but I felt her talents as a woodcarver and seamstress would be wasted. She could make dresses like no princess had ever seen, and as for her carving skills—my! Wood seemed to melt at her touch like butter upon hot, fresh bread. What nobleman wouldn’t give his right arm to have her elegant statues in his dining room or great hall? An Artisan was the path for her, and even though Yelina thought it lowly, she was a great one.<br>
<br>
Ornith—now he was a tough lad. Warriors had to have discipline. Ornith had none.     <br>
<br>
He was the practical joker of our family. Once, or in fact, many times, he would balance a full bucket of water on the top of our doorframe, waiting for Father or some other patsy to open the door and get soaked. He was also the king of snakes, frogs, and mice, grabbing them and putting them on our chairs or beds. He’d make a fine rat-catcher, one of many possible Servants’ duties, but I knew his fierce pride wouldn’t let him do it. Servanthood was not for him, Ornith sneered, and if the Priests made him one, he’d run away from our town and live in exile. Good gracious, I hoped not! Ornith was my closest brother! What would I do without his jokes, wit, and honest views of life?<br>
<br>
Aiya—now she was the sister I worried about. Her frailty and anxiety did not lend itself well to the six classes our town had. If anyone would be a Priest in our house, it would probably be Aiya. She had a spiritual awareness that even the knights who served the priests marveled at. Yelina was jealous of her. In fact, she was so fiercely jealous that she threatened to reveal what happened to Aiya to our town’s Warriors. No one could join the Priesthood if they weren’t pure, and Aiya, on a dare from her foolish friends, had stolen gold from one of our town’s richer merchants. If she were found out, Aiya would spend five years in prison, and there would be no chance of my sister being a Priest.<br>
<br>
And then there was me, Ytra, Adventurer-to-be. Five children, quintuplets, we were. <br>
<br>
Destiny was in our blood, although what destiny, none of us could ever figure out!  <br>
<br>
<br>
